Q: How do you sort a stack using recursion (no extra data structures allowed except the call stack)?
link: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/problems/sort-a-stack/1
ğŸ§  You are given a stack of integers. Sort it in ascending order using only recursion and the stack itself.
ğŸ” Do not use any loops or extra stack/array. 
or
Q: Dry run: How does recursion sort the stack [3, 1, 4, 2] (top to bottom)?
Use only recursion (no loops or extra data structures).
Explain step-by-step how the stack is sorted using sortStack() and insertInSortedOrder().

âœ… Recursive Intuition
We use two functions:
sortStack(stack) â†’ Recursively sorts the stack
insertInSortedOrder(stack, element) â†’ Inserts element in correct position
âœ… Code (C++ Beginner-Friendly)
cpp
CopyEdit
void insertInSortedOrder(stack<int>& s, int element) {
    // Base case: stack is empty or top element is smaller
    if (s.empty() || s.top() <= element) {
        s.push(element);
        return;
    }

    // Remove top and recur
    int topElement = s.top();
    s.pop();
    insertInSortedOrder(s, element);

    // Put back the top element
    s.push(topElement);
}

void sortStack(stack<int>& s) {
    // Base case: 0 or 1 element
    if (s.empty() || s.size() == 1) return;

    // Remove top element
    int topElement = s.top();
    s.pop();

    // Sort remaining stack
    sortStack(s);

    // Insert in sorted order
    insertInSortedOrder(s, topElement);
}
ğŸ§  How it works:
Think like selection sort: take out one element, sort the rest, then insert it back in correct position.
Recursion handles both "sort" and "insert" parts using stackâ€™s own memory.
ğŸ•’ Time Complexity: O(NÂ²)
ğŸ’¾ Space Complexity: O(N) due to recursion call stack 
or solution
We want to sort stack [3, 1, 4, 2] from top to bottom using recursion.
ğŸ“š Step-by-step Dry Run
Initial Stack:
Top â†’ [3, 1, 4, 2] â† Bottom
ğŸ” sortStack() Steps (Peeling Phase):
Pop 3 â†’ sort [1, 4, 2]
Pop 1 â†’ sort [4, 2]
Pop 4 â†’ sort [2]
Pop 2 â†’ now empty â†’ return
ğŸ” insertInSortedOrder() Steps (Rebuilding Phase):
Now insert elements back in sorted order:
Insert 2 â†’ stack: [2]
Insert 4
top 2 < 4 â†’ push â†’ [2, 4]
Insert 1
top 4 > 1 â†’ pop
top 2 > 1 â†’ pop
stack empty â†’ push 1 â†’ [1]
push 2 â†’ [1, 2]
push 4 â†’ [1, 2, 4]
Insert 3
top 4 > 3 â†’ pop
top 2 < 3 â†’ push â†’ [1, 2, 3]
push 4 â†’ [1, 2, 3, 4]
âœ… Final Sorted Stack:
Top â†’ [1, 2, 3, 4] â† Bottom
ğŸ“Œ Summary
You recursively remove all elements â†’ base case: empty stack
Then insert them back one by one in the correct position using another recursion
Think of it like:
Peel â†’ sort â†’ insert back properly
